  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Initiating Document Creation**\n\nI\'ve got the initial setup for Google Docs creation using the Docs API. I\'m focusing on the `POST` request to `https://docs.googleapis.com/v1/documents`. The plan is to create documents with a JSON body including a title parameter, such as \"Story Title - A1 English.\"\n\n\n**Refining Content Insertion**\n\nI\'m now focusing on formatting the content within the document after creation, using the `batchUpdate` method. I will use `insertText` requests, but now I\'m considering CEFR levels and languages. I\'m also planning for chapter lengths and overall story length, leading me to think about a chapter-by-chapter dynamic generation interface to avoid exceeding prompt limitations.\n\n\n**Structuring Story Generation**\n\nI\'ve decided to prioritize a structured story generation flow. The focus is now on creating an interactive \"Story Generator\" interface. Users will define parameters like language, CEFR level, genre, and chapter count. The first step will be outlining the story (title, premise, chapter titles/descriptions). After this, they can generate chapters individually or all at once. Generating chapters individually is perfect as this enables a more user-friendly interface.\n\n\n**Adding Vocabulary Features**\n\nI\'m now integrating vocabulary terms. I\'m having the text generator create vocabulary lists (word, definition, translation, pronunciation) along with the story text. The user can export the story with vocabulary to a Google Doc, which I\'ll format properly.\nI\'m evaluating whether this will be a full-stack or client-side application. The need to call Gemini API from the server side steers me towards full-stack, but let me double-check the logic.\n\n\n**Confirming Full-Stack Implementation**\n\nI\'ve confirmed a full-stack architecture is necessary due to the need to securely handle the Gemini API calls alongside Google Docs export with OAuth. The existing file tree strongly supports this direction, with installed dependencies for Express, Vite, Tailwind CSS, React, and the Gemini API. There is no `server.ts` file yet, and that will be my next focus.\n\n\n**Prioritizing OAuth Configuration**\n\nI\'ve hit a critical point: OAuth configuration is now the immediate priority before any Google Workspace code. Specifically, I must implement OAuth with the proper scopes for Google Docs creation, along with user profile data. I\'m focusing on the necessary scopes, which are `https://www.googleapis.com/auth/documents`,  `https://www.googleapis.com/auth/userinfo.profile`, and `https://www.googleapis.com/auth/userinfo.email`. These will allow document creation, user sign-in, and profile access respectively. Next, I need to call `set_up_oauth`.\n\n\n**Evaluating Firebase Usage**\n\nI\'m now determining whether to use Firebase Firestore or local storage for story persistence. Since this is a single-user app and persistence across devices isn\'t essential, I\'m leaning toward simple local storage. I\'ve also confirmed that `set_up_oauth` will handle Firebase Authentication, so I don\'t need to explicitly call `set_up_firebase`. I need to configure the OAuth flow with the required scopes: documents, profile, and email.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I will inspect `metadata.json` to configure the application\'s metadata and descriptive name properly before initiating the OAuth flow for Google Docs."
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 9
      nanos: 36978604
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
