  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Examining architecture details**\n\nI\'ve just noticed the absence of `server.ts` in `package.json`, which is an important clue. Now I\'m carefully reviewing the environment constraints, specifically focusing on the full-stack architecture requirement. I see the mandate for `/api/*` routes, a proxy, and API key protection, which affects all future progress.\n\n\n**Constructing backend elements**\n\nI\'m now focused on the necessary backend setup. I need to create a `server.ts` file and configure it to handle API requests securely. I need to replace the scripts in `package.json` to include the full-stack build and start commands provided in the prompt. I\'m focusing on initializing the server-side API handling, including API key protection and proxying requests. I\'m excited to start!\n\n\n**Refining chapter generation strategy**\n\nI\'m now changing my strategy for the `/api/stories/generate-chapter` endpoint. It\'s clear that generating an entire story at once, even with its stated chapter limits, is not optimal. I\'m focusing on making the process more interactive, enabling incremental chapter generation. This avoids timeout and token limit issues. The user will be able to choose language, CEFR level, and theme/genre.\n\n\n**Designing story state model**\n\nI\'m now fully immersed in designing a comprehensive state/data model for a story. I\'m focusing on the user flow for chapter generation: slice of life, optional keywords, and the \"Start Story\" button. Now, I\'ll generate Chapter 1, display it, extract vocabulary, and allow the user to proceed chapter-by-chapter, or auto-generate the next chapters sequentially. I\'m considering having a \"Build Complete Story\" button.\n\n\n**Defining story structures**\n\nI\'m now deep in defining the data structures for vocabulary, chapters, and the overall story. The vocabulary term interface has fields for the word, part of speech, definition, and context sentence. I\'ve designed the chapter interface to include chapter number, title, content, and the vocabulary list. Finally, the story interface encompasses the story\'s ID, title, language, CEFR level, genre, chapter count, individual chapters, creation timestamp, and a completion status. I\'m focusing on ensuring these structures accurately represent a story and its components.\n\n\n**Defining JSON schema**\n\nI\'m now focusing on defining a JSON schema for chapter generation responses. I\'m prioritizing clarity and comprehensiveness for both `title`, `content`, and especially, `vocabulary` outputs. I\'m structuring the `vocabulary` array, ensuring properties like `word`, `partOfSpeech`, `definition`, and `contextSentence` are fully defined.\n\n\n**Considering context inclusion**\n\nI\'m now thinking about providing context for chapter generation. It\'s obvious that to continue a story, I need to provide metadata like title, language, level, and genre. I can summarize past chapters\' content to give the model the story so far. I\'m focusing on crafting prompts for Chapter N (where N > 1) which include the story metadata, a history summary, and instructions.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I am going to create the types file `/src/types.ts` to declare our types and interfaces for the story generator, which ensures modularity and type-safety across the application."
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 9
      nanos: 406098841
