    thinking: "**Designing the Export Function**\n\nOkay, so I\'ve got `/src/lib/auth.ts` set up and ready to go for logging in and accessing the Google Docs API. But now I\'m shifting focus to actually creating and formatting the documents. I\'m starting to think through the design of that export function\342\200\224how it will work, what its steps should be\342\200\224with a REST call to the Google Docs API.\n\n\n**Building the Content Structure**\n\nI\'m now diving into the specifics of content structuring. My current plan is to compile the story chapters into a structured markdown-style text format. This includes the story title, CEFR level, language, genre, and a clear breakdown of each chapter with titles, content, and vocabulary reviews. I\'m building a helper function that packages this entire markdown, ready to be inserted into the Google Doc.\n\n\n**Implementing the Google Doc Export**\n\nI\'m now implementing the Google Docs export function. I\'ve got the basic structure for creating a new Google Doc using the Google Docs API and handling the authorization flow. I\'m focusing on the HTTP request using the access token, error handling, and extracting the document ID. Next, I\'ll deal with formatting the content to write into the document.\n\n\n**Refining the Text Formatting**\n\nI\'m currently refining the markdown structure for each chapter. My code loops through each chapter, adding the chapter number and title. I\'m focusing on ensuring each section is clearly delineated with lines, content, and the vocabulary list. The goal is to provide a clean and well-structured document, ready for batch insertion into the Google Doc. I\'ve built a single block of text for each chapter, with proper headings, and key vocabularly.\n\n\n**Finalizing the Google Docs Export**\n\nThe export function is now working flawlessly! I\'m using an efficient `insertText` request with a clean JSON body to insert the formatted markdown content into the newly created Google Doc at index 1. Error handling is robust, and if everything goes right, I\'m returning a direct link to the editable Google Doc. This should meet the Google Doc and \"easy reading\" requirements beautifully!\n\n\n**Integrating the Story Elements**\n\nI\'m now integrating several key elements to enhance the user experience. I\'m focusing on features such as selecting 7 to 10 chapters, incorporating vocabulary reviews, a vocabulary card deck, and a matching game. I\'m also ensuring story history is saved to `localStorage` for local persistence. I\'m also going for seamless dark mode implementation, and fluid animations for the user interface using `motion/react`. I\'m starting to write a utility file to bring everything together beautifully. Also, I\'m checking the current typography setup in `src/index.css`.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I am going to edit `/src/index.css` to add typography rules importing the modern Inter sans-serif font for the user interface, Lora serif for the book text to enable reading pleasure, and modern JetBrains Mono for learning stats and tags."
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 7
      nanos: 581081107
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
